{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625927"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17049"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17049"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.05,0.07,0.05,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9739"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55542"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4836"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5136"},{"type":"tags","id":"5138"},{"type":"tags","id":"5772"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23064"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23523"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EStimulant laxatives are commonly used medications that promote bowel movements by increasing intestinal motility and fluid secretion. There are some circumstances where these agents should not be used.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the strongest contraindication to their use?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Suspected mechanical bowel obstruction","Advanced age","Recent antibiotic use","Chronic constipation","Pregnancy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuspected mechanical bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E is an absolute contraindication to stimulant laxative use. Increasing intestinal motility in the presence of a mechanical obstruction could lead to further colonic distension, followed by perforation, peritonitis, and other serious complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are not absolute contraindications:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvanced age\u003C/strong\u003E is not a contraindication, though careful dosing may be required due to altered metabolism and increased sensitivity in elderly patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecent antibiotic use\u003C/strong\u003E may alter bowel flora and habits but does not prevent the safe use of stimulant laxatives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic constipation\u003C/strong\u003E can be treated with stimulant laxatives, though they are not typically first-line therapy and should be used intermittently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a contraindication, and certain stimulant laxatives may be used safely when dietary measures and bulk-forming agents are insufficient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStimulant laxatives should be used cautiously and for short periods. They work by irritating the intestinal mucosa to increase motility and fluid secretion. Common examples include bisacodyl and senna.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Stimulant laxatives are contraindicated in suspected bowel obstruction due to risk of bowel perforation.","Stimulant laxatives work by increasing intestinal motility and fluid secretion through direct action on the colonic mucosa.","Common stimulant laxatives include bisacodyl and senna."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Par\u00e9 P, Fedorak RN. Systematic review of stimulant and nonstimulant laxatives for the treatment of functional constipation. Can J Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2014 Nov;28(10):549-57. doi: 10.1155/2014/631740. PMID: 25390617; PMCID: PMC4234355."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55542"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17049"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55542"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T17:22:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T17:23:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9739"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70079"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":